1
00:00:04,560 --> 00:00:06,400
(BELL TOLLING)

2
00:00:09,080 --> 00:00:11,640
NARRATOR: In London,
in the time of Queen Victoria,

3
00:00:11,720 --> 00:00:13,960
there were many tales
of a remarkable personage

4
00:00:14,040 --> 00:00:16,440
known as the Great Detective.

5
00:00:16,520 --> 00:00:19,920
I refer, of course, to Madame Vastra,

6
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:24,720
the lizard woman of Paternoster Row
and her extraordinary adventures,

7
00:00:24,800 --> 00:00:27,280
her beautiful assistant Jenny Flint

8
00:00:29,320 --> 00:00:31,760
and their mysterious henchman Strax,

9
00:00:31,840 --> 00:00:35,520
whose countenance was too abominable
to be photographed.

10
00:00:43,880 --> 00:00:45,040
What?

11
00:00:45,120 --> 00:00:48,920
There are also accounts of a fourth
member of the Paternoster Gang,

12
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:54,640
a shadowy figure whose assistance was
only sought in the direst emergencies.

13
00:00:54,720 --> 00:00:56,920
I'm so glad you came.

14
00:00:57,480 --> 00:01:01,400
We have news, I think,
of particular interest to you.

15
00:01:02,480 --> 00:01:04,720
There was a meteor shower
in the southwest,

16
00:01:04,800 --> 00:01:07,400
unexpected timing and density.

17
00:01:07,480 --> 00:01:11,680
I have calculated there is a 34% chance
it is the result of alien intervention.

18
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:15,480
Twenty-four percent.

19
00:01:16,680 --> 00:01:20,920
Well, they could just be meteors
but it's worth looking into.

20
00:01:21,600 --> 00:01:24,800
There is a very pleasant tea room
in the area.

21
00:01:25,880 --> 00:01:29,400
Also, there's a Professor Erasmus Pink,

22
00:01:29,480 --> 00:01:32,640
who's claiming he's going to
split the world open with a giant drill

23
00:01:32,720 --> 00:01:34,880
through the thinnest part
of the Earth's crust.

24
00:01:34,960 --> 00:01:36,480
I think we should investigate.

25
00:01:37,760 --> 00:01:41,160
I mean,
he doesn't actually have a giant drill

26
00:01:41,240 --> 00:01:43,480
and he's not really a professor

27
00:01:43,560 --> 00:01:45,480
and he was a bit drunk at the time
and singing a bit

28
00:01:45,560 --> 00:01:50,760
but, you know, it's never too early
to investigate a drill.

29
00:01:52,760 --> 00:01:55,000
I've declared war on the moon!

30
00:01:55,560 --> 00:01:57,160
-Do be quiet, Strax.
-(SIGHS)

31
00:01:57,240 --> 00:02:00,760
Too long the moon has hung unmonitored
and unsuspected in the sky.

32
00:02:00,840 --> 00:02:03,120
It has gained
an enormous tactical advantage.

33
00:02:03,200 --> 00:02:04,360
There's no one living there.

34
00:02:04,880 --> 00:02:08,680
Then it is clearly time to act.
They won't suspect a thing.

35
00:02:09,320 --> 00:02:11,240
Who won't suspect a thing?

36
00:02:12,400 --> 00:02:14,360
Moonites.

37
00:02:15,840 --> 00:02:18,840
Why do you keep doing this?
What is the point?

38
00:02:22,040 --> 00:02:23,920
I have told you,

39
00:02:24,040 --> 00:02:28,240
I keep telling you,
I don't do this any more.

40
00:02:29,360 --> 00:02:31,160
I've retired.

41
00:02:32,160 --> 00:02:34,840
There's a man on Praed Street
with an invisible wife.

42
00:02:36,880 --> 00:02:39,720
Maybe he just doesn't have a wife.

43
00:02:43,240 --> 00:02:45,080
You're wasting your time.

44
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:47,680
Merry Christmas!

45
00:02:51,720 --> 00:02:53,480
I think he means it.

46
00:02:53,560 --> 00:02:57,400
Yes, my dear. I rather think he does.

47
00:03:05,720 --> 00:03:07,600
Damn moon.

